This approach is not working. Let's think more carefully about what `foldl1` does.

`foldl1 f a [b, c, ...]` is `f (f a b) c ...`.
So `foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) [t] ++ ts` is `((Tree.leaf x).node t).node ...` for the rest of `ts`.

So `spine (foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) [t] ++ ts)` is `spine ((Tree.leaf x).node t) ++ ...`.
`spine ((Tree.leaf x).node t)` is `spine (Tree.leaf x) ++ [t]` which is `[[x]] ++ [t]` = `[x, t]`.

The induction hypothesis `ih` is `spine (foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) ts) = [x] ++ ts`.
So `spine (foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) [t] ++ ts)` is `spine ((Tree.leaf x).node (foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) ts)) ++ ...`.
This is `spine (foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) ts) ++ [foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) ts] ++ ...`.
By induction hypothesis, this is `([x] ++ ts) ++ [foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) ts] ++ ...`.

We need to show this equals `[x] ++ t :: ts`.
This is `x :: (t :: ts)` which is `[x, t, ...]`.

So we need to show `([x] ++ ts) ++ [foldl1 .node (Tree.leaf x) ts] ++ ... = [x, t, ...]`.
This should be true by the induction hypothesis. Let's try to make this precise.

